In the case of the precipitation of TFLX FF, the effect of buffer species and buffer capacity can be explained by their effect on the surface pH [11, 19, 25, 29]. The rates of precipitation processes (both nucleation and particle growth) depend on the supersaturation ratio (SR) of TFLX FF against the intrinsic solubility (S0) (SR = [TFLX]ss/ S0, where the subscript ss indicates the supersaturated concentration). At the surface of TFLX TS, the solution is in equilibrium with the solid of TFLX TS, so that the concentration of protonated TFLX becomes constant ([TFLX∙H+]ss = Ksp,TFLX TS1/2). At pH <  < pKa2, the concentration of the anionic form is negligible. Therefore, the supersaturation ratio of TFLX FF (SRTFLX FF) is expressed as,1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
